    <text>
        <body>
            <head>193. Telegram From the Secretary of State’s Delegation to the <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d193fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Executive Secretariat, S/S-IRM Records, Memoranda of Conversations Pertaining to
                    United States and <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> Relations, 1981–1990,
                    Lot 93D188, Moscow trip—<gloss target="#t_MEMCON_1">Memcons</gloss> 4/12–16/87.
                    Secret; Immediate.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="simple_right #right">
                    <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1987-04-14T23:00:00+00:00">April 14, 1987, 2300<gloss target="#t_Z_1"
                            >Z</gloss>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>Secto 6017. Subj: April 14 <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">start</rs>
                working session</p>
            <p>1. (Secret—Entire text).</p>
            <p>2. Summary: In a two-hour, ten-minute April 14 working group meeting on <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>, Ambassadors <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> and
                    <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> dealt with <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>, <gloss
                    target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> limits and deployed/non-deployed <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>. <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> resisted <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> (beyond a fifty percent
                cut in heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>’s); called for functionally-related differences and shipboard <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="reclbsHvbXLer8sMP">on-site inspection</rs> to distinguish
                between nuclear- and conventionally-armed <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s (but offered no concrete ideas); and said the Soviets were prepared to
                address the deployed/non-deployed missile issue in a positive manner. End
                Summary.</p>
            <pb facs="0881" n="854" xml:id="pg_854"/>
            <p>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recYKTo2QC0yLpT7N">Draft treaty</rs> vs. key elements</p>
            <p>3. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> noted <persName
                    corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>’s comment (April 13) that
                the sides should concentrate their efforts on achieving an <gloss
                    target="#t_LRINF_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="reczU3lVS4eZr8vxf">LRINF</rs>
                </gloss> treaty and a key elements agreement covering <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recIIt0FIMFrHm5mM">space</rs> and <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">strategic offensive arms</rs>. <persName
                    corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> recalled that <persName
                    corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName> had termed <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">strategic arms reductions</rs> the “root” of the <rs
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs> problem; the U.S.
                intended to table a <rs type="topic" corresp="recYKTo2QC0yLpT7N">draft treaty</rs>
                text next round, and saw no reason the sides could not conclude a <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> treaty this year. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName>
                asked that the U.S. not exclude the possibility of a key elements agreement.</p>
            <p>
                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">Sublimits</rs>
            </p>
            <p>4. In a discussion which dominated most of the meeting, <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> dismissed <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> as “irrelevant” within
                the context of a fifty percent reduction of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">strategic offensive arms</rs>. They had not been
                agreed in <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>. The sides
                could discuss an eighty to eighty-five percent missile <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warhead</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> and a sixty percent <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> on weapons on any one leg
                of a side’s <rs corresp="rechRXFB0v2ifZPIR" type="compound-subject">triad</rs>, but
                only in the case that each bomb and <gloss target="#t_SRAM_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recJJ92wdIeZoqUpd">SRAM</rs>
                </gloss> were counted as a single weapon within the weapons aggregate. <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> stated that the sides should be
                free to determine their own force structures; the U.S. proposal—even if
                implementation of reductions were lengthened from five to seven years—still
                represented an attempt to restructure Soviet <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic forces</rs>, according to a U.S. plan that
                was not consistent with Soviet security.</p>
            <p>5. <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> rejected <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName>’s assertion that the <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rule</rs> for bombs and <gloss
                    target="#t_SRAM_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recJJ92wdIeZoqUpd">SRAM</rs>
                </gloss>’s had made a <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic
                    missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warhead</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> irrelevant. The U.S. had
                accepted the <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rule</rs> on the assumption
                that there would be missile <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                    >warhead</rs>
                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs>. This U.S. concern was
                well-known to the Soviet side; it was, moreover, hard to understand why the <gloss
                    target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> now would not accept a concept (missile <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warhead</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs>) or level (eighty
                percent) that it had earlier itself proposed. This question was not resolved; there
                could be no <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement without <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic"
                    >sublimits</rs>.</p>
            <p>6. <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> rejected the charge that
                the U.S. had agreed to drop <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic"
                    >sublimits</rs>, and said the Soviet proposal to offer the <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> in the first place had
                helped with the climate which resulted in the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik meeting</rs> and the progress there. For
                    <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> to suggest that
                dropping <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> had been the
                price for the <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rule</rs> was to suggest that
                net progress had not been made at <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc"
                    >Reykjavik</rs> by the two heads of state. Rather the Soviets’ had given with
                one hand while taking away with the other. Furthermore, for <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> to suggest that the <rs
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> question had been closed
                at <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs> would imply that the
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> joint working document seeking to resolve this and other issues was not
                being worked in good faith by the Soviet side and that the Soviet side was not
                negotiating seriously here in Moscow.</p>
            <pb facs="0882" n="855" xml:id="pg_855"/>
            <p>
                <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>7. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> conceded that the Soviets
                had agreed in principle at <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc"
                    >Reykjavik</rs> to limit nuclear-armed <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s only, but the problem was how to distinguish nuclear from conventional
                systems. The Soviets had thus proposed to treat all <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s as nuclear-armed, to facilitate <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45"
                    type="topic">verification</rs>. But they had also suggested that non-nuclear
                    <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s have some functionally-related differences, and that <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reclbsHvbXLer8sMP">on-site inspection</rs> on each sides’ naval vessels
                would be necessary. These ideas offered grounds for saying that there had been some
                narrowing of differences on this issue.</p>
            <p>8. <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> responded that the U.S.
                would not accept conventional <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> limits. The U.S. was ready to consider the question of limitation of
                nuclear long-ranged <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s, but didn’t know how such limits could be verified. In response to
                    <persName corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName>’s questioning, <persName
                    corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> did not provide any examples of
                functionally-related observable differences for nuclear vs. conventional <gloss
                    target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>’s.</p>
            <p>Deployed/<rs type="topic" corresp="recPOh1SDhDLLFZPg">non-deployed missiles</rs>
            </p>
            <p>9. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> said the Soviets were
                prepared to approach the question of the terms “deployed” and “non-deployed” <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs> positively. But
                the sides would have to agree on what was meant by “deployed” and
                “non-deployed.”</p>
            <p>10. <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc">Obukhov</persName> and <persName
                    corresp="recJgMRnt6OpkXR5T">Lehman</persName> agreed to report to ministers on
                their exchanges.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">
                        <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                    </hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
